The paper proposes a novel type of function learning network that can learn analytical expressions and is able to extrapolate to unseen domains. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of end-to-end differentiable feed-forward networks, which are commonly used in Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) research. The paper also mentions the use of sparsity regularization, which is a common technique in Neural Engineering (cs.NE) research. The paper's focus on identifying concise and interpretable expressions suggests that it may also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. Finally, the paper's use of gradient-based training and potential applications in computer vision suggest that it may also belong to the Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (cs.CV) sub-category.
